<tt>Wed Dec  3  6:43:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Paul,<br><br>
Thanks for the message. I remember back to 1968 and the Prague Spring. I wasn't very old, yet I wondered at that time why the US didn't get involved in the rebellion in Czechoslovakia. A sovereign nation, Czechoslovakia, eventually was  invaded by another country - the Soviet Union. I was only 19 years old, yet could understand much better a true cause as represented by moderates within the Czech government and the Czech populace which supported them. Yet we sat back and watched. It was not the first time that we did nothing in Eastern Europe.<br><br>
A friend once told me that, &quot;people get the kind of government they deserve&quot;. Thankfully, a generation later, the shackles of communism were broken in Europe. It took the people to break them - not US forces. There is a certain truth involved when people refer to the Reagan arms build up as being a factor in the downfall of the Communist Empire. The bottom line, however, was the people of that region willing to risk all in the name of freedom.<br><br>
It is my belief that the 2 Vietnamese Wars were first, a war by people to rid themselves of foreign colonial exploitation. Second, a war of reunification. A civil war in which the best organized force, the communists, won out over the side which was viewed as the continued extension of colonialism - ruling class of elitists - the Diems. <br><br>
Let's stop looking at the situation with our american eyes and start looking as if we were Vietnamese and we may be able to understand better. Were all who fought against us hard line communists, or were most of them  people who felt they had no representation in the South Vietnamese government? Shouldn't we look at the fact that we were aligned with Communist governments during WWII in order to beat back the forces of world wide facism? Was it up to us to decide if Thieu or the Diem family were &quot;preferable to Ho&quot;? Or was it a decision that should have been made by the Vietnamese? Who would have won the election in 1956?<br><br>
In my view the war was a civil war, and not a war where one country was invading the other - as in the case of Czechoslovakia being overrun by Soviet armor and infantry.<br><br>
We define our military involvement in terms of national interest. Which region, Europe or Indo China, better represents our national interest? How about Cuba - 90 miles away? Why aren't we there?<br><br>

